{"slug": "necromancer", "root": "necromancer", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a raiser of the dead", "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Greek nekromanteia: nekros (‘corpse’) + manteia (‘divination’)", "first": "‘nigromancy’ in Middle English", "note": "Originally divination BY the dead, not raising them. Medieval Latin folk-etymologised it to nigromantia — ‘black arts’ — swapping death for the colour black.", "hook": "How ‘death-divination’ became ‘the black arts’ by a spelling mistake.", "lang": "Greek"}, "essay": {"title": "Necromancer: how death-divination became the black arts", "dek": "A single mistaken vowel turned a diviner who listens to the dead into a sorcerer who commands them.", "read_min": 3, "html": "<p>A <strong>necromancer</strong>, to a Greek, was not someone who raised the dead to fight for them. The word is <em>nekromanteia</em> — <em>nekros</em>, 'corpse,' plus <em>manteia</em>, 'divination.' It named a specific ancient practice: summoning the spirits of the dead not as servants but as <em>informants</em>. Odysseus performs it in <em>Odyssey</em> XI, digging a pit of blood so the shades will speak. It belongs, properly, with <a href=\"atlas.html#divination\">divination</a> — with scrying and augury — not with armies of the dead.</p><p>So how did the necromancer become the corpse-puppeteer of modern fantasy? Partly through a spelling accident, and Ted's databases document the drift. Medieval Latin, uneasy with the Greek, reshaped <em>necromantia</em> into <strong>nigromantia</strong> — as if from <em>niger</em>, 'black.' Death-divination was folk-etymologised into 'the black arts.' The RenaissanceMagicDB entry for <em>necromantia</em> preserves the original sense exactly — 'summoning or consulting the spirits of the dead to obtain hidden knowledge' — while Frank Klaassen's <em>The Transformations of Magic</em> and Claire Fanger's studies of ritual magic (<em>Invoking Angels</em>; <em>Rewriting Magic</em>) trace how the learned conjuring of spirits was recast, by hostile authorities, as the blackest of the illicit arts. Michael Bailey's <em>The Sacred and the Sinister</em> maps precisely that boundary-work.</p><p>Magic: The Gathering inherits the fantasy necromancer wholesale — the corpus overwhelmingly reanimates. But the older meaning is the better story, because it turns on a single mistaken letter. Change one vowel-cluster in a monk's Latin and you convert a diviner who <em>listens</em> to the dead into a sorcerer who <em>commands</em> them. Words, like the dead, don't always stay where you put them.</p>", "sources": [{"label": "RenaissanceMagicDB, s.v. necromantia", "where": "RenaissanceMagicDB"}, {"label": "Frank Klaassen, The Transformations of Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Claire Fanger, Invoking Angels; Rewriting Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Michael D. Bailey et al., The Sacred and the Sinister: Studies in Medieval Religion and Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. necromancy (‹ Greek nekromanteia; med.L. nigromantia)", "where": "Etymology reference"}]}, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 53, "oracle_total": 2, "in_flavor_cards": 51, "in_oracle_cards": 2, "name_match_count": 20, "by_variant": {"necromancer": 32, "necromancers": 11, "necromancy": 9, "necromantic": 3}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"B": 61, "R": 4, "U": 3, "W": 2, "G": 3, "C": 1}, "by_year": {"1994": 1, "1995": 7, "1997": 1, "2005": 1, "2006": 4, "2008": 7, "2009": 1, "2010": 3, "2011": 1, "2012": 1, "2013": 4, "2014": 6, "2015": 3, "2016": 1, "2017": 1, "2018": 3, "2019": 4, "2020": 3, "2021": 6, "2022": 1, "2023": 3, "2024": 6, "2025": 1}}, "cards": [{"id": "b96a8ad2-3d86-459b-a34f-19c9dc07c3c4", "name": "Liliana, Heretical Healer // Liliana, Defiant Necromancer", "set": "CC2", "type_line": "Legendary Creature — Human Cleric // Legendary Planeswalker — Liliana", "rarity": "mythic", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/d/8/d8b718d8-fca3-4b3e-9448-6067c8656a9a.jpg?1782739532", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/d/8/d8b718d8-fca3-4b3e-9448-6067c8656a9a.jpg?1782739532", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/cc2/1/liliana-heretical-healer-liliana-defiant-necromancer?utm_source=api", "local": "img/necromancer/b96a8ad2-3d86-459b-a34f-19c9dc07c3c4.jpg"}, {"id": "f3ad60a6-05d0-48a1-a804-7900d306d613", "name": "Liliana, the Necromancer", "set": "M19", "type_line": "Legendary Planeswalker — Liliana", "rarity": "mythic", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/4/d/4d2cbc2c-dbe3-4ecb-8fbe-785cb80b9e76.jpg?1782709436", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/4/d/4d2cbc2c-dbe3-4ecb-8fbe-785cb80b9e76.jpg?1782709436", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/m19/291/liliana-the-necromancer?utm_source=api", "local": "img/necromancer/f3ad60a6-05d0-48a1-a804-7900d306d613.jpg"}, {"id": "155422a0-a0cd-4399-8ed9-fa68ac2c80a6", "name": "Doomed Necromancer", "set": "AFC", "type_line": "Creature — Human Cleric Mercenary", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/2/d/2d3225e8-9902-4826-9cb3-68ecfaebb1e9.jpg?1782704145", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/2/d/2d3225e8-9902-4826-9cb3-68ecfaebb1e9.jpg?1782704145", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/afc/98/doomed-necromancer?utm_source=api", "local": "img/necromancer/155422a0-a0cd-4399-8ed9-fa68ac2c80a6.jpg"}, {"id": "ccdf3399-b836-47ab-802d-af5a9c24d759", "name": "Draugr Necromancer", "set": "KHM", "type_line": "Snow Creature — Zombie Cleric", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/7/6/76d8e0ff-e720-41ca-af69-35585a2d7ae2.jpg?1782705499", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.i